cholarly or popular attention has focused on women's relationships in antiquity, in contrast to recent interest in the relationships between men in ancient Greece and Rome. The essays in this book seek to close this gap by exploring a wide variety of textual and archaeological evidence for women's homosocial and homoerotic relationships from prehistoric Greece to fifth-century CE Egypt. Drawing on developments in feminist theory, gay and lesbian studies, and queer theory, as well as traditional textual and art historical methods, the contributors to this volume examine representations of women's lives with other women, their friendships, and sexual subjectivity. They present new interpretations of the evidence offered by the literary works of Sappho, Ovid, and Lucian; Bronze Age frescoes and Greek vase painting, funerary reliefs, and other artistic representations; and Egyptian legal documents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAuanger, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAuanger, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGreene, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaley, Shelley P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPintabone, Diane T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabinowitz, Nancy Sorkin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabinowitz, Nancy Sorkin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRehak, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSkinner, Marilyn B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilfong, Terry G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYounger, Jo